docs.abstract: A helicopter and dozens of officers, some in tactical gear, were deployed for an arrest at a Manhattan apartment but withdrew after protesters arrived.
docs.snippet: A helicopter and dozens of officers, some in tactical gear, were deployed for an arrest at a Manhattan apartment but withdrew after protesters arrived.
docs.lead_paragraph: Derrick Ingram, an organizer of a group leading New York’s Black Lives Matter protests, was besieged inside his Manhattan apartment on Friday while a police helicopter patrolled overhead, officers banged on his door and police dogs waited in the hallway.

headline.main: N.Y.P.D. Besieges a Protest Leader as He Broadcasts Live
headline.print_headline: Black Lives Matter Protest Leader Livestreams the N.Y.P.D. Pounding on His Door

docs.abstract: Residents on Minneapolis’s North Side, which has a majority Black population, have mixed opinions on the City Council’s effort to significantly reduce the police force.
docs.snippet: Residents on Minneapolis’s North Side, which has a majority Black population, have mixed opinions on the City Council’s effort to significantly reduce the police force.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — The burgundy Oldsmobile sped through an intersection in a tree-lined residential neighborhood on Minneapolis’s North Side, and Lisa Williams shook her head in disgust.

headline.main: Distrust of the Minneapolis Police, and Also the Effort to Defund Them
headline.print_headline: In Black Areas of Minneapolis, Some Doubt Calls to Defund Police

docs.abstract: The boycotts, including games in the W.N.B.A., Major League Baseball and Major League Soccer, come as athletes have wondered whether speaking out against systemic racism would be enough to influence change.
docs.snippet: The boycotts, including games in the W.N.B.A., Major League Baseball and Major League Soccer, come as athletes have wondered whether speaking out against systemic racism would be enough to influence change.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. — Athletes from the N.B.A., W.N.B.A., Major League Baseball and Major League Soccer took their boldest stand yet against systemic racism and police brutality, boycotting games on Wednesday in response to the police shooting of a Black man in Kenosha, Wis. The moves dramatically escalated a season of athletes demonstrating for social justice as some expressed doubts about continuing to play amid widespread social unrest.

headline.main: Led by N.B.A., Boycotts Disrupt Pro Sports in Wake of Blake Shooting

docs.abstract: A Minnesota judge ordered that footage from cameras worn by two officers be publicly released. Here’s what that footage tells us. These videos include graphic imagery.
docs.snippet: A Minnesota judge ordered that footage from cameras worn by two officers be publicly released. Here’s what that footage tells us. These videos include graphic imagery.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nearly 11 weeks after George Floyd was killed by the police in Minneapolis, inciting a wave of protests across the United States, a Minnesota county court has released police body camera footage of the episode to the public for the first time.

headline.main: New Footage Shows Delayed Medical Response to George Floyd

docs.abstract: A powerful visitors’ bureau has pushed the South Carolina city to the top of “best” lists by selling gentility. Critics say that has come at the expense of history and the city’s Black population.
docs.snippet: A powerful visitors’ bureau has pushed the South Carolina city to the top of “best” lists by selling gentility. Critics say that has come at the expense of history and the city’s Black population.
docs.lead_paragraph: The week that George Floyd was killed by Minneapolis police officers, the Charleston, S.C., Convention & Visitors Bureau introduced a campaign to assure tourists that despite the coronavirus pandemic, Charleston — a city that has topped must-go travel lists for years — was ready to welcome them back.

headline.main: Charleston Tourism Is Built on Southern Charm. Locals Say It’s Time to Change.

byline.original: By Tariro Mzezewa and Kim Severson

docs.abstract: This documentary on the race-related killing of the Black teenager Yusuf Hawkins in 1989 never settles on a satisfying point of view.
docs.snippet: This documentary on the race-related killing of the Black teenager Yusuf Hawkins in 1989 never settles on a satisfying point of view.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Aug. 23, 1989, a Black teenager named Yusuf K. Hawkins was fatally shot in Bensonhurst, Brooklyn, after being surrounded by a group of white youths, an incident of race-related violence that became a lightning rod in New York and beyond. In the wake of George Floyd protests, the documentary “Yusuf Hawkins: Storm Over Brooklyn” could scarcely be timelier.

headline.main: ‘Storm Over Brooklyn’ Review: A Flash Point of Racial Violence

docs.abstract: Cori Bush, an activist backed by the progressive group Justice Democrats, is trying to unseat 10-term Representative William Lacy Clay in a bid to turn protest-movement fervor into hard political power.
docs.snippet: Cori Bush, an activist backed by the progressive group Justice Democrats, is trying to unseat 10-term Representative William Lacy Clay in a bid to turn protest-movement fervor into hard political power.
docs.lead_paragraph: FERGUSON, Mo. — As an activist who jumped into the political arena after the police shooting of Michael Brown here six years ago, Cori Bush is accustomed to hard fights. She has been maced, shot at with rubber bullets and cloaked in tear gas at so many protests against police brutality that they have blurred together.

headline.main: In St. Louis, Testing Liberal Might Against a Democratic Fixture
headline.print_headline: Progressive in St. Louis Aims to Topple a Dynasty

docs.abstract: How would Nashville be different if it hadn’t pushed the trio away? A conversation about “Gaslighter” and beyond.
docs.snippet: How would Nashville be different if it hadn’t pushed the trio away? A conversation about “Gaslighter” and beyond.
docs.lead_paragraph: After the killing of George Floyd and the protests for racial justice that followed, the Dixie Chicks finally unloaded their old name because of its unwelcome associations with the Old South. After rebranding as the Chicks, the group released “Gaslighter,” its first new album in 14 years.

headline.main: The Welcome Return of the Chicks
